-- Crude Options Volatility Falls as Underlying Options Increase
-- B y   D a n   M u r t a u g h
-- 2013-07-25T20:20:25Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-25/crude-options-volatility-falls-as-underlying-options-increase.html
Crude oil options volatility fell as
September futures rose.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options value, was 21.46 percent on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  as of 3:40 p.m., down from 21.83 yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery rose
10 cents, or 0.1 percent, to $105.49 a barrel on the Nymex.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
September $100 puts, which slipped 12 cents to 55 cents a barrel
on volume of 3,150 lots traded as of 3:43 p.m. September $115
calls were the second-most active, retreating 3 cents to 10
cents a barrel on volume of 2,975 contracts.  Puts accounted for 59 percent of electronic trading volume.
In the prior session, bearish bets made up 57 percent of 117,828
contracts exchanged.  September $100 puts were the most-active options yesterday
with 10,599 contracts changing hands as they gained 25 cents to
67 cents a barrel. September $95 puts increased 8 cents to 21
cents on 5,518 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
38,336 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 37,653 lots
and December $70 puts with 35,010.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
